Following the bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, Sudan condemned the American attacks on their embassy in Khartoum.
President Clinton's actions were viewed as a diversion tactic by many Arabs.
Sudan sought a UN investigation into the US claims.
The destroyed pharmaceutical plant was defended by Sudanese officials as not producing chemical weapons.
Despite skepticism, Sudan vowed to prove the plant's innocence.
The presence of Sudanese security forces at the site raised doubts about its true nature.
The incident further fueled anti-American sentiments in the region, with many criticizing the US for its actions.
